`test_passes` starts as `false` (RED). After implementation, verify with `cargo test` and set to `true` (GREEN).

The contract (`contract_code`) MUST be a `///` doc-comment on the function signature with all layers: `expect:` (verbal, user's voice, structural origin point), `[P{N}] Motivating:` (goal principle), `[P{N}] Constraining:` (zero to many constraint principles, minimum all applicable P1-P4 Magna Carta), and `pre:`/`post:` (behavioral specification). It is written before any test code.

The test function must carry a descriptive doc comment referencing the contract's `expect:` statement immediately above the `#[test]` attribute.

## Constraints

- **Contract first, test second, implementation third.** Per Testing Discipline §6.3 and Process Rule P1. The contract is the specification of the test.
- Exactly ONE contract, ONE test, ONE behavior. Minimal implementation.
- The contract must include all layers: `expect:` with `[P{N}]` tag (verbal, user's voice, structural origin point), `[P{N}] Constraining:` (zero to many constraint principles, minimum all applicable P1-P4 Magna Carta), and `pre:`/`post:` (behavioral specification).
- The `expect:` statement must use the `[P{N}] Motivating:` annotation for the goal principle.
- Test must fail before implementation is added.
- Implementation must be the minimum to satisfy the contract without violating constraining principles.
- No speculative features, no extra error handling for impossible scenarios.
- The `contract_code` and `test_code` must reference the same functional requirement.
- The contract must use `/// expect:` + `[P{N}]` annotation format.
- Do not execute arbitrary Python code in Jinja2 expressions (sandboxed execution).
- Preserve the original prompt structure and formatting.
- Handle missing variables gracefully (leave as-is or use default if specified).

